{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ebad4705-2416-469c-961f-b777ceb2915a","content":"You have a few options to get `dotnet-trace` into an SDK-less container:\n\n### 1. Install as a global tool (requires .NET SDK)\nNot applicable here since you don't have the SDK.\n\n### 2. Download the standalone distribution (recommended)\n`dotnet-trace` is available as a self-contained binary — no SDK needed:\n\n```bash\n# From inside the container (or copy in after downloading)\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o dotnet-trace\nchmod +x dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Collect the trace\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n./dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can copy out and analyze with **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (`--format speedscope`).\n\n### Tips\n- Use `./dotnet-trace ps` to list available .NET processes.\n- Add `--duration 00:00:30` to auto-stop after 30 seconds.\n- For `arm64` containers, replace `linux-x64` with `linux-arm64` in the download URL.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"88459c7e-2f57-42c0-9dbd-b4e3814352a6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU. This is a general .NET diagnostics question - I can answer from knowledge.","outputTokens":367,"requestId":"784D:322F45:1E6BDCD:21B77FA:69FA9919"},"id":"8e0e8be6-eeca-41d9-9c28-276016f8ae68","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:28:04.165Z","parentId":"4ba3f60f-d3f1-4eae-9530-c9c94989ca66"}
